\par CREATING A GHOST
\par }\pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs19\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20 \'93Ghost\'94
 is an acquired template that can be added to any aberration, animal, dragon, giant, humanoid, magical beast, monstrous humanoid, or plant. The creature (referred to hereafter as the base creature) must have a Charisma score of at least 6.
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20 A ghost uses all the base creature\rquote s statistics and special abilities except as noted here.
\par }{\b\fs20 Size and Type:}{\fs20  The creature\rquote s type changes to undead. Do not recalculate the creature\rquote s base attack bonus, saves, or skill points. It gains the incorporeal subtype. Size is unchanged.
\par }{\b\fs20 Hit Dice:}{\fs20  All current and future Hit Dice become d12s.
\par }{\b\fs20 Speed:}{\fs20  Ghosts have a fly speed of 30 feet, unless the base creature has a higher fly speed, with perfect maneuverability. 
\par }{\b\fs20 Armor Class:}{\fs20  Natural armor is the same as the base creature\rquote 
s but applies only to ethereal encounters. When the ghost manifests (see below), its natural armor bonus is +0, but it gains a deflection bonus equal to its Charisma modifier or +1, whichever is higher.
\par }{\b\fs20 Attack:}{\fs20  A ghost retains all the attacks of the base creature, although those relying on physical contact do not affect creatures that are not ethereal.
\par }{\b\fs20 Full Attack:}{\fs20  A ghost retains all the attacks of the base creature, although those relying on physical contact do not affect creatures that are not ethereal.
\par }{\b\fs20 Damage:}{\fs20  Against ethereal creatures, a ghost uses the base creature\rquote s damage values. Against nonethereal creatures, the ghost usually cannot deal physical damage at all but can use its special attacks, if any, when it manifests 
(see below).
\par }{\b\fs20 Special Attacks:}{\fs20 
 A ghost retains all the special attacks of the base creature, although those relying on physical contact do not affect nonethereal creatures. The ghost also gains a manifestation ability plus one to three other special attacks
 as described below. The save DC against a special attack is equal to 10 + 1/2 ghost\rquote s HD + ghost\rquote s Cha modifier unless otherwise noted.
\par }{\i\fs20 Corrupting Gaze (Su): }{\fs20 A ghost can blast living beings with a glance, at a range of up to 30 feet. Creatures that meet the ghost\rquote 
s gaze must succeed on a Fortitude save or take 2d10 points of damage and 1d4 points of Charisma damage.
\par }{\i\fs20 Corrupting Touch (Su): }{\fs20 A ghost that hits a living target with its incorporeal touch attack deals 1d6 points of damage. Against ethereal oppone
nts, it adds its Strength modifier to attack and damage rolls. Against nonethereal opponents, it adds its Dexterity modifier to attack rolls only.
\par }{\i\fs20 Draining Touch (Su): }{\fs20 A ghost that hits a living target with its incorporeal touch attack drains 1d4 points fr
om any one ability score it selects. On each such successful attack, the ghost heals 5 points of damage to itself. Against ethereal opponents, it adds its Strength modifier to attack rolls only. Against nonethereal opponents, it adds its Dexterity modifie
r to attack rolls only.
\par }{\i\fs20 Frightful Moan (Su): }{\fs20 A ghost can emit a frightful moan as a standard action. All living creatures within a 30-foot spread must succeed on a Will save or become panicked for 2d4 rounds. This is a sonic necromantic mind-affecting fear 
effect. A creature that successfully saves against the moan cannot be affected by the same ghost\rquote s moan for 24 hours.
\par }{\i\fs20 Horrific Appearance (Su): }{\fs20 Any living creature within 60 feet that views a ghost must succeed on a Fortitude save or immediately take 1d4 p
oints of Strength damage, 1d4 points of Dexterity damage, and 1d4 points of Constitution damage. A creature that successfully saves against this effect cannot be affected by the same ghost\rquote s horrific appearance for 24 hours.
\par }{\i\fs20 Malevolence (Su): }{\fs20 Once per round, an ethereal ghost can merge its body with a creature on the Material Plane. This ability is similar to a }{\i\fs20 magic jar }{\fs20 spell (caster level 10th or the ghost\rquote 
s Hit Dice, whichever is higher), except that it does not require a receptacle. To use this ability, the ghost must be manifested and it must try move into the target\rquote s space; moving into the target\rquote 
s space to use the malevolence ability does not provoke attacks of opportunity. The target can resist the attack with a successful Will save (DC 15 + ghost\rquote s Cha modifier). A creature that successfully saves is immune to that same ghost\rquote 
s malevolence for 24 hours, and the ghost cannot enter the target\rquote s space. If the save fails, the ghost vanishes into the target\rquote s body.
\par }{\i\fs20 Manifestation (Su): }{\fs20 Every ghost has thi
s ability. A ghost dwells on the Ethereal Plane and, as an ethereal creature, it cannot affect or be affected by anything in the material world. When a ghost manifests, it partly enters the Material Plane and becomes visible but incorporeal on the Materia
l
 Plane. A manifested ghost can be harmed only by other incorporeal creatures, magic weapons, or spells, with a 50% chance to ignore any damage from a corporeal source. A manifested ghost can pass through solid objects at will, and its own attacks pass thr
o
ugh armor. A manifested ghost always moves silently. A manifested ghost can strike with its touch attack or with a ghost touch weapon (see Ghostly Equipment, below). A manifested ghost remains partially on the Ethereal Plane, where is it not incorporeal. 
A manifested ghost can be attacked by opponents on either the Material Plane or the Ethereal Plane. The ghost\rquote s incorporeality helps protect it from foes on the Material Plane, but not from foes on the Ethereal Plane.
\par When a spellcasting ghost is not manife
sted and is on the Ethereal Plane, its spells cannot affect targets on the Material Plane, but they work normally against ethereal targets. When a spellcasting ghost manifests, its spells continue to affect ethereal targets and can affect targets on the M
aterial Plane normally unless the spells rely on touch. A manifested ghost\rquote s touch spells don\rquote t work on nonethereal targets.
\par A ghost has two home planes, the Material Plane and the Ethereal Plane. It is not considered extraplanar when on either of these planes.
\par }{\i\fs20 Telekinesis (Su): }{\fs20 A ghost can use }{\i\fs20 telekinesis }{\fs20 as a standard action (caster level 12th or equal to the ghost\rquote s HD, whichever is higher). When a ghost uses this power, it must wait 1d4 rounds before using it again.

\par }{\b\fs20 Special Qualities:}{\fs20  A ghost has all the special qualities of the base creature as well as those described below.
\par }{\i\fs20 Rejuvenation (Su): }{\fs20 In most cases, it\rquote s difficult to destroy a ghost through simple combat: The \'93destroyed\'94 spirit will often restore itself in 2d4 days. Even the most powerful spells
 are usually only temporary solutions. A ghost that would otherwise be destroyed returns to its old haunts with a successful level check (1d20 + ghost\rquote 
s HD) against DC 16. As a rule, the only way to get rid of a ghost for sure is to determine the reason fo
r its existence and set right whatever prevents it from resting in peace. The exact means varies with each spirit and may require a good deal of research.
\par }{\i\fs20 Turn Resistance (Ex): }{\fs20 A ghost has +4 turn resistance.
\par }{\b\fs20 Abilities:}{\fs20  Same as the base creature, except that the ghost has no Constitution score, and its Charisma score increases by +4. 
\par }{\b\fs20 Skills:}{\fs20  Ghosts have a +8 racial bonus on Hide, Listen, Search, and Spot checks. Otherwise same as the base creature.
\par }{\b\fs20 Environment: }{\fs20 Any, often as base creature.
\par }{\b\fs20 Organization:}{\fs20  Solitary, gang (2\endash 4), or mob (7\endash 12).
\par }{\b\fs20 Challenge Rating: }{\fs20 Same as the base creature +2.
\par }{\b\fs20 Treasure: }{\fs20 None.
\par }{\b\fs20 Alignment: }{\fs20 Any.
\par }{\b\fs20 Level Adjustment: }{\fs20 Same as the base creature +5.
